abstract: Oracle’s profit excluding certain one-time costs rose to 62 cents a share, topping 56 cents, the average estimate of analysts.
snippet: Oracle’s profit excluding certain one-time costs rose to 62 cents a share, topping 56 cents, the average estimate of analysts.
lead_paragraph: Oracle, the biggest maker of database software, exceeded analysts’ estimates for quarterly profit and new license sales on Tuesday, a sign of buoyant demand for programs that help companies organize data and run operations.

headline.main: Software Licenses Help Oracle Beat Estimates
headline.print_headline: Software Licenses Help Oracle Beat Estimates
